# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: physically-based-rendering
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:physically-based-rendering/albedo] While directional-hemispherical reflectance factor is calculated for a single angle of incidence (i.e., for a given position of the Sun), albedo is the directional integration of reflectance over all solar angles in a given period.
[src:physically-based-rendering/albedo] The temporal resolution may range from seconds (as obtained from flux measurements) to daily, monthly, or annual averages.
[src:physically-based-rendering/albedo] Unless given for a specific wavelength (spectral albedo), albedo refers to the entire spectrum of solar radiation.
[src:physically-based-rendering/albedo] Due to measurement constraints, it is often given for the spectrum in which most solar energy reaches the surface (between 0.3 and 3 μm).
[src:physically-based-rendering/albedo] This spectrum includes visible light (0.4–0.7 μm), which explains why surfaces with a low albedo appear dark (e.g., trees absorb most radiation), whereas surfaces with a high albedo appear bright (e.g., snow reflects most radiation).
[src:physically-based-rendering/albedo] Ice–albedo feedback is a positive feedback climate process where a change in the area of ice caps, glaciers, and sea ice alters the albedo and surface temperature of a planet.
[src:physically-based-rendering/albedo] Ice is very reflective, therefore it reflects far more solar energy back to space than the other types of land area or open water.
[src:physically-based-rendering/albedo] Ice–albedo feedback plays an important role in global climate change.
[src:physically-based-rendering/albedo] Albedo is an important concept in climate science.
[src:physically-based-rendering/albedo] The albedo in visible light ranges from about 0.9 to 0.95 for fresh snow to about 0.04 for charcoal, one of the darkest substances.
[src:physically-based-rendering/albedo] Deeply shadowed cavities can achieve an effective albedo approaching the zero of a black body.
[src:physically-based-rendering/albedo] When seen from a distance, the ocean surface has a low albedo, as do most forests, whereas desert areas have some of the highest albedos among landforms.
[src:physically-based-rendering/albedo] Most land areas are in an albedo range of 0.1 to 0.4.
[src:physically-based-rendering/albedo] The average albedo of Earth is about 0.3.
[src:physically-based-rendering/albedo] This is far higher than for the ocean primarily because of the contribution of clouds.
[src:physically-based-rendering/albedo] Earth's surface albedo is regularly estimated via Earth observation satellite sensors such as NASA's MODIS instruments on board the Terra and Aqua satellites, and the CERES instrument on the Suomi NPP and JPSS.
[src:physically-based-rendering/albedo] These calculations are based on the bidirectional reflectance distribution function (BRDF), which describes how the reflectance of a given surface depends on the view angle of the observer and the solar angle.
[src:physically-based-rendering/albedo] BDRF can facilitate translations of observations of reflectance into albedo.
[src:physically-based-rendering/albedo] Earth's average surface temperature due to its albedo and the greenhouse effect is currently about 15 °C (59 °F).
[src:physically-based-rendering/albedo] If Earth were frozen entirely (and hence be more reflective), the average temperature of the planet would drop below −40 °C (−40 °F).
[src:physically-based-rendering/albedo] If only the continental land masses became covered by glaciers, the mean temperature of the planet would drop to about 0 °C (32 °F).
[src:physically-based-rendering/albedo] In contrast, if the entire Earth was covered by water – a so-called ocean planet – the average temperature on the planet would rise to almost 27 °C (81 °F).
[src:physically-based-rendering/albedo] In 2021, scientists reported that Earth dimmed by ~0.5% over two decades (1998–2017) as measured by earthshine using modern photometric techniques.
[src:physically-based-rendering/albedo] This may have both been co-caused by climate change as well as a substantial increase in global warming.
[src:physically-based-rendering/albedo] However, the link to climate change has not been explored to date and it is unclear whether or not this represents an ongoing trend.
[src:physically-based-rendering/albedo] This formula is important because it allows the albedo to be calculated for any given illumination conditions from a knowledge of the intrinsic properties of the surface.
[src:physically-based-rendering/albedo] Human activities (e.g., deforestation, farming, and urbanization) change the albedo of various areas around the globe.
[src:physically-based-rendering/albedo] Human impacts to "the physical properties of the land surface can perturb the climate by altering the Earth's radiative energy balance" even on a small scale or when undetected by satellites.
[src:physically-based-rendering/albedo] Urbanization generally decreases albedo (commonly being 0.01–0.02 lower than adjacent croplands), which contributes to global warming.
[src:physically-based-rendering/albedo] Deliberately increasing albedo in urban areas can mitigate the urban heat island effect.
[src:physically-based-rendering/albedo] Intentionally enhancing the albedo of the Earth's surface, along with its daytime thermal emittance, has been proposed as a solar radiation management strategy to mitigate energy crises and global warming known as passive daytime radiative cooling (PDRC).
[src:physically-based-rendering/albedo] Efforts toward widespread implementation of PDRCs may focus on maximizing the albedo of surfaces from very low to high values, so long as a thermal emittance of at least 90% can be achieved.
[src:physically-based-rendering/albedo] The tens of thousands of hectares of greenhouses in Almería, Spain form a large expanse of whitened plastic roofs.
[src:physically-based-rendering/albedo] A 2008 study found that this anthropogenic change lowered the local surface area temperature of the high-albedo area, although changes were localized.
[src:physically-based-rendering/albedo] A follow-up study found that "CO2-eq. emissions associated to changes in surface albedo are a consequence of land transformation" and can reduce surface temperature increases associated with climate change.
[src:physically-based-rendering/albedo] However, albedo and illumination both vary by latitude.
[src:physically-based-rendering/albedo] Albedo is highest near the poles and lowest in the subtropics, with a local maximum in the tropics.
[src:physically-based-rendering/albedo] Tropical and sub-tropical rainforest areas have low albedo, and are much hotter than their temperate forest counterparts, which have lower insolation.
[src:physically-based-rendering/albedo] Because insolation plays such a big role in the heating and cooling effects of albedo, high insolation areas like the tropics will tend to show a more pronounced fluctuation in local temperature when local albedo changes.
[src:physically-based-rendering/albedo] Arctic regions notably release more heat back into space than what they absorb, effectively cooling the Earth.
[src:physically-based-rendering/albedo] Since arctic ice and snow have been melting at higher rates due to higher temperatures, creating regions in the arctic that are notably darker (being water or ground which is darker color), there is concern because less heat is reflected back into space.
[src:physically-based-rendering/albedo] This feedback loop results in a reduced albedo effect.
[src:physically-based-rendering/albedo] Albedo affects climate by determining how much radiation a planet absorbs.
[src:physically-based-rendering/albedo] The uneven heating of Earth from albedo variations between land, ice, or ocean surfaces can drive weather.
[src:physically-based-rendering/albedo] The response of the climate system to an initial forcing is modified by feedbacks: increased by "self-reinforcing" or "positive" feedbacks and reduced by "balancing" or "negative" feedbacks.
[src:physically-based-rendering/albedo] The main reinforcing feedbacks are the water-vapour feedback, the ice–albedo feedback, and the net effect of clouds.
[src:physically-based-rendering/albedo] When an area's albedo changes due to snowfall, a snow–temperature feedback results.
[src:physically-based-rendering/albedo] A layer of snowfall increases local albedo, reflecting away sunlight, leading to local cooling.
[src:physically-based-rendering/albedo] In principle, if no outside temperature change affects this area (e.g., a warm air mass), the raised albedo and lower temperature would maintain the current snow and invite further snowfall, deepening the snow–temperature feedback.
[src:physically-based-rendering/albedo] However, because local weather is dynamic due to the change of seasons, eventually warm air masses and a more direct angle of sunlight (higher insolation) cause melting.
[src:physically-based-rendering/albedo] When the melted area reveals surfaces with lower albedo, such as grass, soil, or ocean, the effect is reversed: the darkening surface lowers albedo, increasing local temperatures, which induces more melting and thus reducing the albedo further, resulting in still more heating.
[src:physically-based-rendering/albedo] Snow albedo is highly variable, ranging from as high as 0.9 for freshly fallen snow, to about 0.4 for melting snow, and as low as 0.2 for dirty snow.
[src:physically-based-rendering/albedo] Over Antarctica, snow albedo averages a little more than 0.8.
[src:physically-based-rendering/albedo] If a marginally snow-covered area warms, snow tends to melt, lowering the albedo, and hence leading to more snowmelt because more radiation is being absorbed by the snowpack (referred to as the ice–albedo positive feedback).
[src:physically-based-rendering/albedo] In Switzerland, the citizens have been protecting their glaciers with large white tarpaulins to slow down the ice melt.
[src:physically-based-rendering/albedo] These large white sheets are helping to reject the rays from the sun and defecting the heat.
[src:physically-based-rendering/albedo] Although this method is very expensive, it has been shown to work, reducing snow and ice melt by 60%.
[src:physically-based-rendering/albedo] Just as fresh snow has a higher albedo than does dirty snow, the albedo of snow-covered sea ice is far higher than that of sea water.
[src:physically-based-rendering/albedo] Sea water absorbs more solar radiation than would the same surface covered with reflective snow.
[src:physically-based-rendering/albedo] When sea ice melts, either due to a rise in sea temperature or in response to increased solar radiation from above, the snow-covered surface is reduced, and more surface of sea water is exposed, so the rate of energy absorption increases.
[src:physically-based-rendering/albedo] The extra absorbed energy heats the sea water, which in turn increases the rate at which sea ice melts.
[src:physically-based-rendering/albedo] As with the preceding example of snowmelt, the process of melting of sea ice is thus another example of a positive feedback.
[src:physically-based-rendering/albedo] Both positive feedback loops have long been recognized as important for global warming.
[src:physically-based-rendering/albedo] Cryoconite, powdery windblown dust containing soot, sometimes reduces albedo on glaciers and ice sheets.
[src:physically-based-rendering/albedo] The dynamical nature of albedo in response to positive feedback, together with the effects of small errors in the measurement of albedo, can lead to large errors in energy estimates.
[src:physically-based-rendering/albedo] Because of this, in order to reduce the error of energy estimates, it is important to measure the albedo of snow-covered areas through remote sensing techniques rather than applying a single value for albedo over broad regions.
[src:physically-based-rendering/albedo] In sunlight, dark clothes absorb more heat and light-coloured clothes reflect it better, thus allowing some control over body temperature by exploiting the albedo effect of the colour of external clothing.
[src:physically-based-rendering/albedo] Albedo can affect the electrical energy output of solar photovoltaic devices.
[src:physically-based-rendering/albedo] Research showed impacts of over 10% for vertically (90°) mounted systems, but such effects were substantially lower for systems with lower surface tilts.
[src:physically-based-rendering/albedo] Spectral albedo strongly affects the performance of bifacial solar cells where rear surface performance gains of over 20% have been observed for c-Si cells installed above healthy vegetation.
[src:physically-based-rendering/albedo] Forests generally have a low albedo because the majority of the ultraviolet and visible spectrum is absorbed through photosynthesis.
[src:physically-based-rendering/albedo] For this reason, the greater heat absorption by trees could offset some of the carbon benefits of afforestation (or offset the negative climate impacts of deforestation).
[src:physically-based-rendering/albedo] In other words: The climate change mitigation effect of carbon sequestration by forests is partially counterbalanced in that reforestation can decrease the reflection of sunlight (albedo).
[src:physically-based-rendering/albedo] In the case of evergreen forests with seasonal snow cover, albedo reduction may be significant enough for deforestation to cause a net cooling effect.
[src:physically-based-rendering/albedo] Trees also impact climate in extremely complicated ways through evapotranspiration.
[src:physically-based-rendering/albedo] The water vapor causes cooling on the land surface, causes heating where it condenses, acts as strong greenhouse gas, and can increase albedo when it condenses into clouds.
[src:physically-based-rendering/albedo] Scientists generally treat evapotranspiration as a net cooling impact, and the net climate impact of albedo and evapotranspiration changes from deforestation depends greatly on local climate.
[src:physically-based-rendering/albedo] Mid-to-high-latitude forests have a much lower albedo during snow seasons than flat ground, thus contributing to warming.
[src:physically-based-rendering/albedo] Modeling that compares the effects of albedo differences between forests and grasslands suggests that expanding the land area of forests in temperate zones offers only a temporary mitigation benefit.
[src:physically-based-rendering/albedo] In seasonally snow-covered zones, winter albedos of treeless areas are 10% to 50% higher than nearby forested areas because snow does not cover the trees as readily.
[src:physically-based-rendering/albedo] Deciduous trees have an albedo value of about 0.15 to 0.18 whereas coniferous trees have a value of about 0.09 to 0.15.
[src:physically-based-rendering/albedo] Variation in summer albedo across both forest types is associated with maximum rates of photosynthesis because plants with high growth capacity display a greater fraction of their foliage for direct interception of incoming radiation in the upper canopy.
[src:physically-based-rendering/albedo] The result is that wavelengths of light not used in photosynthesis are more likely to be reflected back to space rather than being absorbed by other surfaces lower in the canopy.
[src:physically-based-rendering/albedo] Studies by the Hadley Centre have investigated the relative (generally warming) effect of albedo change and (cooling) effect of carbon sequestration on planting forests.
[src:physically-based-rendering/albedo] They found that new forests in tropical and midlatitude areas tended to cool; new forests in high latitudes (e.g., Siberia) were neutral or perhaps warming.
[src:physically-based-rendering/albedo] Research in 2023, drawing from 176 flux stations globally, revealed a climate trade-off: increased carbon uptake from afforestation results in reduced albedo.
[src:physically-based-rendering/albedo] Initially, this reduction may lead to moderate global warming over a span of approximately 20 years, but it is expected to transition into significant cooling thereafter.
[src:physically-based-rendering/albedo] Water reflects light very differently from typical terrestrial materials.
[src:physically-based-rendering/albedo] The reflectivity of a water surface is calculated using the Fresnel equations.
[src:physically-based-rendering/albedo] At the scale of the wavelength of light even wavy water is always smooth so the light is reflected in a locally specular manner (not diffusely).
[src:physically-based-rendering/albedo] The glint of light off water is a commonplace effect of this.
[src:physically-based-rendering/albedo] At small angles of incident light, waviness results in reduced reflectivity because of the steepness of the reflectivity-vs.-incident-angle curve and a locally increased average incident angle.
[src:physically-based-rendering/albedo] Although the reflectivity of water is very low at low and medium angles of incident light, it becomes very high at high angles of incident light such as those that occur on the illuminated side of Earth near the terminator (early morning, late afternoon, and near the poles).
[src:physically-based-rendering/albedo] However, as mentioned above, waviness causes an appreciable reduction.
[src:physically-based-rendering/albedo] Because light specularly reflected from water does not usually reach the viewer, water is usually considered to have a very low albedo in spite of its high reflectivity at high angles of incident light.
[src:physically-based-rendering/albedo] Note that white caps on waves look white (and have high albedo) because the water is foamed up, so there are many superimposed bubble surfaces which reflect, adding up their reflectivities.
[src:physically-based-rendering/albedo] Fresh 'black' ice exhibits Fresnel reflection.
[src:physically-based-rendering/albedo] Snow on top of this sea ice increases the albedo to 0.9.
[src:physically-based-rendering/albedo] Cloud albedo has substantial influence over atmospheric temperatures.
[src:physically-based-rendering/albedo] Different types of clouds exhibit different reflectivity, theoretically ranging in albedo from a minimum of near 0 to a maximum approaching 0.8.
[src:physically-based-rendering/albedo] "On any given day, about half of Earth is covered by clouds, which reflect more sunlight than land and water.
[src:physically-based-rendering/albedo] Albedo and climate in some areas are affected by artificial clouds, such as those created by the contrails of heavy commercial airliner traffic.
[src:physically-based-rendering/albedo] A study following the burning of the Kuwaiti oil fields during Iraqi occupation showed that temperatures under the burning oil fires were as much as 10 °C (18 °F) colder than temperatures several miles away under clear skies.
[src:physically-based-rendering/albedo] Aerosols (very fine particles/droplets in the atmosphere) have both direct and indirect effects on Earth's radiative balance.
[src:physically-based-rendering/albedo] The direct (albedo) effect is generally to cool the planet; the indirect effect (the particles act as cloud condensation nuclei and thereby change cloud properties) is less certain.
[src:physically-based-rendering/albedo] Another albedo-related effect on the climate is from black carbon particles.
[src:physically-based-rendering/albedo] The size of this effect is difficult to quantify: the Intergovernmental Panel on Climate Change estimates that the global mean radiative forcing for black carbon aerosols from fossil fuels is +0.2 W m−2, with a range +0.1 to +0.4 W m−2.
[src:physically-based-rendering/albedo] Black carbon is a bigger cause of the melting of the polar ice cap in the Arctic than carbon dioxide due to its effect on the albedo.
[src:physically-based-rendering/albedo] In astronomy, the term **albedo** can be defined in several different ways, depending upon the application and the wavelength of electromagnetic radiation involved.
[src:physically-based-rendering/albedo] The albedos of planets, satellites and minor planets such as asteroids can be used to infer much about their properties.
[src:physically-based-rendering/albedo] The study of albedos, their dependence on wavelength, lighting angle ("phase angle"), and variation in time composes a major part of the astronomical field of photometry.
[src:physically-based-rendering/albedo] For small and far objects that cannot be resolved by telescopes, much of what we know comes from the study of their albedos.
[src:physically-based-rendering/albedo] For example, the absolute albedo can indicate the surface ice content of outer Solar System objects, the variation of albedo with phase angle gives information about regolith properties, whereas unusually high radar albedo is indicative of high metal content in asteroids.
[src:physically-based-rendering/albedo] Enceladus, a moon of Saturn, has one of the highest known optical albedos of any body in the Solar System, with an albedo of 0.99.
[src:physically-based-rendering/albedo] Another notable high-albedo body is Eris, with an albedo of 0.96.
[src:physically-based-rendering/albedo] Many small objects in the outer Solar System and asteroid belt have low albedos down to about 0.05.
[src:physically-based-rendering/albedo] A typical comet nucleus has an albedo of 0.04.
[src:physically-based-rendering/albedo] Such a dark surface is thought to be indicative of a primitive and heavily space weathered surface containing some organic compounds.
[src:physically-based-rendering/albedo] The overall albedo of the Moon is measured to be around 0.14, but it is strongly directional and non-Lambertian, displaying also a strong opposition effect.
[src:physically-based-rendering/albedo] Although such reflectance properties are different from those of any terrestrial terrains, they are typical of the regolith surfaces of airless Solar System bodies.
[src:physically-based-rendering/albedo] Two common optical albedos that are used in astronomy are the (V-band) geometric albedo (measuring brightness when illumination comes from directly behind the observer) and the Bond albedo (measuring total proportion of electromagnetic energy reflected).
[src:physically-based-rendering/albedo] Their values can differ significantly, which is a common source of confusion.
[src:physically-based-rendering/albedo] In detailed studies, the directional reflectance properties of astronomical bodies are often expressed in terms of the five Hapke parameters which semi-empirically describe the variation of albedo with phase angle, including a characterization of the opposition effect of regolith surfaces.
[src:physically-based-rendering/albedo] One of these five parameters is yet another type of albedo called the single-scattering albedo.
[src:physically-based-rendering/albedo] It is used to define scattering of electromagnetic waves on small particles.
[src:physically-based-rendering/albedo] It depends on properties of the material (refractive index), the size of the particle, and the wavelength of the incoming radiation.
[src:physically-based-rendering/albedo] An important relationship between an object's astronomical (geometric) albedo, absolute magnitude and diameter is given by: $A=\left({\frac {1329\times 10^{-H/5}}{D}}\right)^{2},$ where A is the astronomical albedo, D is the diameter in kilometers, and H is the absolute magnitude.
[src:physically-based-rendering/albedo] In planetary radar astronomy, a microwave (or radar) pulse is transmitted toward a planetary target (e.g.
[src:physically-based-rendering/albedo] Moon, asteroid, etc.) and the echo from the target is measured.
[src:physically-based-rendering/albedo] In most instances, the transmitted pulse is circularly polarized and the received pulse is measured in the same sense of polarization as the transmitted pulse (SC) and the opposite sense (OC).
[src:physically-based-rendering/albedo] The echo power is measured in terms of radar cross-section, ${\sigma }_{OC}$ , ${\sigma }_{SC}$ , or ${\sigma }_{T}$ (total power, SC + OC) and is equal to the cross-sectional area of a metallic sphere (perfect reflector) at the same distance as the target that would return the same echo power.
[src:physically-based-rendering/albedo] Those components of the received echo that return from first-surface reflections (as from a smooth or mirror-like surface) are dominated by the OC component as there is a reversal in polarization upon reflection.
[src:physically-based-rendering/albedo] If the surface is rough at the wavelength scale or there is significant penetration into the regolith, there will be a significant SC component in the echo caused by multiple scattering.
[src:physically-based-rendering/albedo] where the denominator is the effective cross-sectional area of the target object with mean radius, r .
[src:physically-based-rendering/albedo] A smooth metallic sphere would have ${\hat {\sigma }}_{\text{OC}}=1$ .
[src:physically-based-rendering/albedo] The values reported for the Moon, Mercury, Mars, Venus, and Comet P/2005 JQ5 are derived from the total (OC+SC) radar albedo reported in those references.
[src:physically-based-rendering/albedo] The term albedo was introduced into optics by Johann Heinrich Lambert in his 1760 work *Photometria*.
[src:physically-based-rendering/bidirectional-scattering-distribution-function] The definition of the **bidirectional scattering distribution function** (**BSDF**) is not well standardized.
[src:physically-based-rendering/bidirectional-scattering-distribution-function] The term was probably introduced in 1980 by Bartell, Dereniak, and Wolfe.
[src:physically-based-rendering/bidirectional-scattering-distribution-function] Most often it is used to name the general mathematical function which describes the way in which the light is scattered by a surface.
[src:physically-based-rendering/bidirectional-scattering-distribution-function] However, in practice, this phenomenon is usually split into the reflected and transmitted components, which are then treated separately as the **bidirectional reflectance distribution function** (**BRDF**) and **bidirectional transmittance distribution function** (**BTDF**) respectively.
[src:physically-based-rendering/fresnel-equations] polarization, despite being poor reflectors at normal incidence.
[src:physically-based-rendering/fresnel-equations] polarization, greatly reducing glare from horizontal surfaces.
[src:physically-based-rendering/fresnel-equations] The **Fresnel equations** (or **Fresnel coefficients**) describe the reflection and transmission of light (or electromagnetic radiation in general) when incident on an interface between different optical media.
[src:physically-based-rendering/fresnel-equations] They were deduced by French engineer and physicist Augustin-Jean Fresnel (/freɪˈnɛl/) who was the first to understand that light is a transverse wave, when no one realized that the waves were electric and magnetic fields.
[src:physically-based-rendering/fresnel-equations] For the first time, polarization could be understood quantitatively, as Fresnel's equations correctly predicted the differing behaviour of waves of the *s* and *p* polarizations incident upon a material interface.
[src:physically-based-rendering/fresnel-equations] When light strikes the interface between a medium with refractive index *n*1 and a second medium with refractive index *n*2, both reflection and refraction of the light may occur.
[src:physically-based-rendering/fresnel-equations] The Fresnel equations give the ratio of the *reflected* wave's electric field to the incident wave's electric field, and the ratio of the *transmitted* wave's electric field to the incident wave's electric field, for each of two components of polarization.
[src:physically-based-rendering/fresnel-equations] (The *magnetic* fields can also be related using similar coefficients.) These ratios are generally complex, describing not only the relative amplitudes but also the phase shifts at the interface.
[src:physically-based-rendering/fresnel-equations] The equations assume the interface between the media is flat and that the media are homogeneous and isotropic.
[src:physically-based-rendering/fresnel-equations] The incident light is assumed to be a plane wave, which is sufficient to solve any problem since any incident light field can be decomposed into plane waves and polarizations.
[src:physically-based-rendering/fresnel-equations] There are two sets of Fresnel coefficients for two different linear polarization components of the incident wave.
[src:physically-based-rendering/fresnel-equations] Since any polarization state can be resolved into a combination of two orthogonal linear polarizations, this is sufficient for any problem.
[src:physically-based-rendering/fresnel-equations] Likewise, unpolarized (or "randomly polarized") light has an equal amount of power in each of two linear polarizations.
[src:physically-based-rendering/fresnel-equations] The s polarization refers to polarization of a wave's electric field *normal* to the plane of incidence (the z direction in the derivation below); then the magnetic field is *in* the plane of incidence.
[src:physically-based-rendering/fresnel-equations] The p polarization refers to polarization of the electric field *in* the plane of incidence (the xy plane in the derivation below); then the magnetic field is *normal* to the plane of incidence.
[src:physically-based-rendering/fresnel-equations] The names "s" and "p" for the polarization components refer to German "senkrecht" (perpendicular or normal) and "parallel" (parallel to the plane of incidence).
[src:physically-based-rendering/fresnel-equations] Although the reflection and transmission are dependent on polarization, at normal incidence (*θ* = 0) there is no distinction between them so all polarization states are governed by a single set of Fresnel coefficients (and another special case is mentioned below in which that is true).
[src:physically-based-rendering/fresnel-equations] In the diagram, an incident plane wave in the direction of the ray **IO** strikes the interface between two media of refractive indices *n*1 and *n*2 at point **O**.
[src:physically-based-rendering/fresnel-equations] Part of the wave is reflected in the direction **OR**, and part refracted in the direction **OT**.
[src:physically-based-rendering/fresnel-equations] The angles that the incident, reflected and refracted rays make to the normal of the interface are given as *θ*i, *θ*r and *θ*t, respectively.
[src:physically-based-rendering/fresnel-equations] The behavior of light striking the interface is explained by considering the electric and magnetic fields that constitute an electromagnetic wave, and the laws of electromagnetism, as shown below.
[src:physically-based-rendering/fresnel-equations] The ratio of waves' electric field (or magnetic field) amplitudes are obtained, but in practice one is more often interested in formulae which determine *power* coefficients, since power (or irradiance) is what can be directly measured at optical frequencies.
[src:physically-based-rendering/fresnel-equations] The power of a wave is generally proportional to the square of the electric (or magnetic) field amplitude.
[src:physically-based-rendering/fresnel-equations] Note that these are what would be measured right *at* each side of an interface and do not account for attenuation of a wave in an absorbing medium *following* transmission or reflection.
[src:physically-based-rendering/fresnel-equations] We assume that the media are non-magnetic (i.e., *μ*1 = *μ*2 = *μ*0), which is typically a good approximation at optical frequencies (and for transparent media at other frequencies).
[src:physically-based-rendering/fresnel-equations] Then the wave impedances are determined solely by the refractive indices *n*1 and *n*2: $Z_{i}={\frac {Z_{0}}{n_{i}}}\,,$ where *Z*0 is the impedance of free space and *i* = 1, 2.
[src:physically-based-rendering/fresnel-equations] The second form of each equation is derived from the first by eliminating *θ*t using Snell's law and trigonometric identities.
[src:physically-based-rendering/fresnel-equations] Note that all such intensities are measured in terms of a wave's irradiance in the direction normal to the interface; this is also what is measured in typical experiments.
[src:physically-based-rendering/fresnel-equations] This complication can be ignored in the case of the reflection coefficient, since cos *θ*i = cos *θ*r, so that the ratio of reflected to incident irradiance in the wave's direction is the same as in the direction normal to the interface.
[src:physically-based-rendering/fresnel-equations] Although these relationships describe the basic physics, in many practical applications one is concerned with "natural light" that can be described as unpolarized.
[src:physically-based-rendering/fresnel-equations] For low-precision applications involving unpolarized light, such as computer graphics, rather than rigorously computing the effective reflection coefficient for each angle, Schlick's approximation is often used.
[src:physically-based-rendering/fresnel-equations] For the case of normal incidence, *θ*i = *θ*t = 0, and there is no distinction between s and p polarization.
[src:physically-based-rendering/fresnel-equations] For common glass (*n*2 ≈ 1.5) surrounded by air (*n*1 = 1), the power reflectance at normal incidence can be seen to be about 4%, or 8% accounting for both sides of a glass pane.
[src:physically-based-rendering/fresnel-equations] At a dielectric interface from *n*1 to *n*2, there is a particular angle of incidence at which *R*p goes to zero and a p-polarised incident wave is purely refracted, thus all reflected light is s-polarised.
[src:physically-based-rendering/fresnel-equations] This angle is known as Brewster's angle, and is around 56° for *n*1 = 1 and *n*2 = 1.5 (typical glass).
[src:physically-based-rendering/fresnel-equations] When light travelling in a denser medium strikes the surface of a less dense medium (i.e., *n*1 > *n*2), beyond a particular incidence angle known as the *critical angle*, all light is reflected and *R*s = *R*p = 1.
[src:physically-based-rendering/fresnel-equations] This phenomenon, known as total internal reflection, occurs at incidence angles for which Snell's law predicts that the sine of the angle of refraction would exceed unity (whereas in fact sin *θ* ≤ 1 for all real *θ*).
[src:physically-based-rendering/fresnel-equations] For glass with *n* = 1.5 surrounded by air, the critical angle is approximately 42°.
[src:physically-based-rendering/fresnel-equations] Reflection at 45° incidence is very commonly used for making 90° turns.
[src:physically-based-rendering/fresnel-equations] This can be used to either verify the consistency of the measurements of *R*s and *R*p, or to derive one of them when the other is known.
[src:physically-based-rendering/fresnel-equations] This relationship is only valid for the simple case of a single plane interface between two homogeneous materials, not for films on substrates, where a more complex analysis is required.
[src:physically-based-rendering/fresnel-equations] Measurements of *R*s and *R*p at 45° can be used to estimate the reflectivity at normal incidence.
[src:physically-based-rendering/fresnel-equations] The "average of averages" obtained by calculating first the arithmetic as well as the geometric average of *R*s and *R*p, and then averaging these two averages again arithmetically, gives a value for *R*0 with an error of less than about 3% for most common optical materials.
[src:physically-based-rendering/fresnel-equations] This is useful because measurements at normal incidence can be difficult to achieve in an experimental setup since the incoming beam and the detector will obstruct each other.
[src:physically-based-rendering/fresnel-equations] However, since the dependence of *R*s and *R*p on the angle of incidence for angles below 10° is very small, a measurement at about 5° will usually be a good approximation for normal incidence, while allowing for a separation of the incoming and reflected beam.
[src:physically-based-rendering/fresnel-equations] The above equations relating powers (which could be measured with a photometer for instance) are derived from the Fresnel equations which solve the physical problem in terms of electromagnetic field complex amplitudes, i.e., considering phase shifts in addition to their amplitudes.
[src:physically-based-rendering/fresnel-equations] Those underlying equations supply generally complex-valued ratios of those EM fields and may take several different forms, depending on the formalism used.
[src:physically-based-rendering/fresnel-equations] The complex amplitude coefficients for reflection and transmission are usually represented by lower case *r* and *t* (whereas the power coefficients are capitalized).
[src:physically-based-rendering/fresnel-equations] As before, we are assuming the magnetic permeability, *µ* of both media to be equal to the permeability of free space *µ*0 as is essentially true of all dielectrics at optical frequencies.
[src:physically-based-rendering/fresnel-equations] In the following equations and graphs, we adopt the following conventions.
[src:physically-based-rendering/fresnel-equations] The transmission coefficient *t* is the ratio of the transmitted wave's complex electric field amplitude to that of the incident wave, for either polarization.
[src:physically-based-rendering/fresnel-equations] The equations consider a plane wave incident on a plane interface at angle of incidence $\theta _{\mathrm {i} }$ , a wave reflected at angle $\theta _{\mathrm {r} }=\theta _{\mathrm {i} }$ , and a wave transmitted at angle $\theta _{\mathrm {t} }$ .
[src:physically-based-rendering/fresnel-equations] In the case of an interface into an absorbing material (where *n* is complex) or total internal reflection, the angle of transmission does not generally evaluate to a real number.
[src:physically-based-rendering/fresnel-equations] In that case, however, meaningful results can be obtained using formulations of these relationships in which trigonometric functions and geometric angles are avoided; the inhomogeneous waves launched into the second medium cannot be described using a single propagation angle.
[src:physically-based-rendering/fresnel-equations] For the case where the magnetic permeabilities are non-negligible, the equations change such that every appearance of $n_{i}$ is replaced by $n_{i}/\mu _{i}$ (for both $i=1,2$ ).
[src:physically-based-rendering/fresnel-equations] One can write very similar equations applying to the ratio of the waves' magnetic fields, but comparison of the electric fields is more conventional.
[src:physically-based-rendering/fresnel-equations] On the other hand, calculation of the power transmission coefficient T is less straightforward, since the light travels in different directions in the two media.
[src:physically-based-rendering/fresnel-equations] What's more, the wave impedances in the two media differ; power (irradiance) is given by the square of the electric field amplitude *divided by* the characteristic impedance of the medium (or by the square of the magnetic field *multiplied by* the characteristic impedance).
[src:physically-based-rendering/fresnel-equations] The introduced factor of ⁠*n*2/*n*1⁠ is the reciprocal of the ratio of the media's wave impedances.
[src:physically-based-rendering/fresnel-equations] The cos(*θ*) factors adjust the waves' powers so they are reckoned *in the direction* normal to the interface, for both the incident and transmitted waves, so that full power transmission corresponds to *T* = 1.
[src:physically-based-rendering/fresnel-equations] In the case of total internal reflection where the power transmission T is zero, t nevertheless describes the electric field (including its phase) just beyond the interface.
[src:physically-based-rendering/fresnel-equations] This is an evanescent field which does not propagate as a wave (thus *T* = 0) but has nonzero values very close to the interface.
[src:physically-based-rendering/fresnel-equations] The phase shift of the reflected wave on total internal reflection can similarly be obtained from the phase angles of *r*p and *r*s (whose magnitudes are unity in this case).
[src:physically-based-rendering/fresnel-equations] These phase shifts are different for *s* and *p* waves, which is the well-known principle by which total internal reflection is used to effect polarization transformations.
[src:physically-based-rendering/fresnel-equations] These formulas are known respectively as *Fresnel's sine law* and *Fresnel's tangent law*.
[src:physically-based-rendering/fresnel-equations] Although at normal incidence these expressions reduce to 0/0, one can see that they yield the correct results in the limit as *θ*i → 0.
[src:physically-based-rendering/fresnel-equations] When light makes multiple reflections between two or more parallel surfaces, the multiple beams of light generally interfere with one another, resulting in net transmission and reflection amplitudes that depend on the light's wavelength.
[src:physically-based-rendering/fresnel-equations] The interference, however, is seen only when the surfaces are at distances comparable to or smaller than the light's coherence length, which for ordinary white light is few micrometers; it can be much larger for light from a laser.
[src:physically-based-rendering/fresnel-equations] An example of interference between reflections is the iridescent colours seen in a soap bubble or in thin oil films on water.
[src:physically-based-rendering/fresnel-equations] Applications include Fabry–Pérot interferometers, antireflection coatings, and optical filters.
[src:physically-based-rendering/fresnel-equations] A quantitative analysis of these effects is based on the Fresnel equations, but with additional calculations to account for interference.
[src:physically-based-rendering/fresnel-equations] The transfer-matrix method, or Rouard's recursive method can be used to solve multiple-surface problems.
[src:physically-based-rendering/fresnel-equations] In 1808, Étienne-Louis Malus discovered that when a ray of light was reflected off a non-metallic surface at the appropriate angle, it behaved like *one* of the two rays emerging from a doubly-refractive calcite crystal.
[src:physically-based-rendering/fresnel-equations] He later coined the term *polarization* to describe this behavior.
[src:physically-based-rendering/fresnel-equations] In 1815, the dependence of the polarizing angle on the refractive index was determined experimentally by David Brewster.
[src:physically-based-rendering/fresnel-equations] In 1821, however, Augustin-Jean Fresnel derived results equivalent to his sine and tangent laws (above), by modeling light waves as transverse elastic waves with vibrations perpendicular to what had previously been called the plane of polarization.
[src:physically-based-rendering/fresnel-equations] The experimental confirmation was reported in a "postscript" to the work in which Fresnel first revealed his theory that light waves, including "unpolarized" waves, were *purely* transverse.
[src:physically-based-rendering/fresnel-equations] Details of Fresnel's derivation, including the modern forms of the sine law and tangent law, were given later, in a memoir read to the French Academy of Sciences in January 1823.
[src:physically-based-rendering/fresnel-equations] That derivation combined conservation of energy with continuity of the *tangential* vibration at the interface, but failed to allow for any condition on the *normal* component of vibration.
[src:physically-based-rendering/fresnel-equations] The first derivation from *electromagnetic* principles was given by Hendrik Lorentz in 1875.
[src:physically-based-rendering/fresnel-equations] In the same memoir of January 1823, Fresnel found that for angles of incidence greater than the critical angle, his formulas for the reflection coefficients (*r*s and *r*p) gave complex values with unit magnitudes.
[src:physically-based-rendering/fresnel-equations] Noting that the magnitude, as usual, represented the ratio of peak amplitudes, he guessed that the argument represented the phase shift, and verified the hypothesis experimentally.
[src:physically-based-rendering/fresnel-equations] Thus he finally had a quantitative theory for what we now call the *Fresnel rhomb* — a device that he had been using in experiments, in one form or another, since 1817 (see *Fresnel rhomb § History*).
[src:physically-based-rendering/fresnel-equations] The success of the complex reflection coefficient inspired James MacCullagh and Augustin-Louis Cauchy, beginning in 1836, to analyze reflection from metals by using the Fresnel equations with a complex refractive index.
[src:physically-based-rendering/fresnel-equations] Thus Fresnel's interpretation of the complex values of his reflection coefficients marked the confluence of several streams of his research and, arguably, the essential completion of his reconstruction of physical optics on the transverse-wave hypothesis (see *Augustin-Jean Fresnel*).
[src:physically-based-rendering/fresnel-equations] Here we systematically derive the above relations from electromagnetic premises.
[src:physically-based-rendering/fresnel-equations] In order to compute meaningful Fresnel coefficients, we must assume that the medium is (approximately) linear and homogeneous.
[src:physically-based-rendering/fresnel-equations] For vacuum, these have the values *ϵ*0 and *μ*0, respectively.
[src:physically-based-rendering/fresnel-equations] Hence we define the *relative* permittivity (or dielectric constant) *ϵ*rel = *ϵ*/*ϵ*0, and the *relative* permeability *μ*rel = *μ*/*μ*0.
[src:physically-based-rendering/fresnel-equations] In optics it is common to assume that the medium is non-magnetic, so that *μ*rel = 1.
[src:physically-based-rendering/fresnel-equations] For ferromagnetic materials at radio/microwave frequencies, larger values of *μ*rel must be taken into account.
[src:physically-based-rendering/fresnel-equations] But, for optically transparent media, and for all other materials at optical frequencies (except possible metamaterials), *μ*rel is indeed very close to 1; that is, *μ* ≈ *μ*0.
[src:physically-based-rendering/fresnel-equations] In optics, one usually knows the refractive index *n* of the medium, which is the ratio of the speed of light in vacuum (c) to the speed of light in the medium.
[src:physically-based-rendering/fresnel-equations] In the analysis of partial reflection and transmission, one is also interested in the electromagnetic wave impedance Z, which is the ratio of the amplitude of **E** to the amplitude of **H**.
[src:physically-based-rendering/fresnel-equations] It is therefore desirable to express *n* and Z in terms of *ϵ* and *μ*, and thence to relate Z to *n*.
[src:physically-based-rendering/fresnel-equations] The last-mentioned relation, however, will make it convenient to derive the reflection coefficients in terms of the wave *admittance* Y, which is the reciprocal of the wave impedance Z.
[src:physically-based-rendering/fresnel-equations] In the case of *uniform plane sinusoidal* waves, the wave impedance or admittance is known as the *intrinsic* impedance or admittance of the medium.
[src:physically-based-rendering/fresnel-equations] This case is the one for which the Fresnel coefficients are to be derived.
[src:physically-based-rendering/fresnel-equations] The value of the expression is unchanged if the position **r** varies in a direction normal to **k**; hence **k** *is normal to the wavefronts*.
[src:physically-based-rendering/fresnel-equations] To advance the phase by the angle *ϕ*, we replace *ωt* by *ωt* + *ϕ* (that is, we replace −*ωt* by −*ωt* − *ϕ*), with the result that the (complex) field is multiplied by *e−iϕ*.
[src:physically-based-rendering/fresnel-equations] So a phase *advance* is equivalent to multiplication by a complex constant with a *negative* argument.
[src:physically-based-rendering/fresnel-equations] This becomes more obvious when the field (**1**) is factored as **Ek** *e**i***k**⋅**r***e**−iωt*, where the last factor contains the time-dependence.
[src:physically-based-rendering/fresnel-equations] That factor also implies that differentiation w.r.t. time corresponds to multiplication by *−iω*.
[src:physically-based-rendering/fresnel-equations] If the argument of *e**i*(⋯) is to be constant, *ℓ* must increase at the velocity $\omega /k\,,\,$ known as the *phase velocity* (*v*p).
[src:physically-based-rendering/fresnel-equations] As usual, we drop the time-dependent factor *e*−*iωt*, which is understood to multiply every complex field quantity.
[src:physically-based-rendering/fresnel-equations] Taking the magnitude equations and substituting from (**2**), we obtain ${\begin{aligned}\mu cH&=nE\\\epsilon cE&=nH\,,\end{aligned}}$ where H and E are the magnitudes of **H** and **E**.
[src:physically-based-rendering/fresnel-equations] Dividing the second result by the first gives $n={\sqrt {\mu _{\text{rel}}\epsilon _{\text{rel}}}}\,.$ For a *non-magnetic* medium (the usual case), this becomes ⁠ $n={\sqrt {\epsilon _{\text{rel}}}}$ ⁠.
[src:physically-based-rendering/fresnel-equations] (Taking the reciprocal of (**5**), we find that the intrinsic *impedance* is ${\textstyle Z={\sqrt {\mu /\epsilon }}}$ .
[src:physically-based-rendering/fresnel-equations] In vacuum this takes the value ${\textstyle Z_{0}={\sqrt {\mu _{0}/\epsilon _{0}}}\,\approx 377\,\Omega \,,}$ known as the impedance of free space.
[src:physically-based-rendering/fresnel-equations] In Cartesian coordinates (*x*, *y*, *z*), let the region *y* < 0 have refractive index *n*1, intrinsic admittance *Y*1, etc., and let the region *y* > 0 have refractive index *n*2, intrinsic admittance *Y*2, etc.
[src:physically-based-rendering/fresnel-equations] Then the *xz* plane is the interface, and the *y* axis is normal to the interface (see diagram).
[src:physically-based-rendering/fresnel-equations] Let **i** and **j** (in bold roman type) be the unit vectors in the *x* and *y* directions, respectively.
[src:physically-based-rendering/fresnel-equations] Let the plane of incidence be the *xy* plane (the plane of the page), with the angle of incidence *θ*i measured from **j** towards **i**.
[src:physically-based-rendering/fresnel-equations] Let the angle of refraction, measured in the same sense, be *θ*t, where the subscript *t* stands for *transmitted* (reserving *r* for *reflected*).
[src:physically-based-rendering/fresnel-equations] In the absence of Doppler shifts, *ω* does not change on reflection or refraction.
[src:physically-based-rendering/fresnel-equations] Hence, by (**2**), the magnitude of the wave vector is proportional to the refractive index.
[src:physically-based-rendering/fresnel-equations] So, for a given *ω*, if we *redefine* k as the magnitude of the wave vector in the *reference* medium (for which *n* = 1), then the wave vector has magnitude *n*1*k* in the first medium (region *y* < 0 in the diagram) and magnitude *n*2*k* in the second medium.
[src:physically-based-rendering/fresnel-equations] For the *s* polarization, the **E** field is parallel to the *z* axis and may therefore be described by its component in the *z* direction.
[src:physically-based-rendering/fresnel-equations] Let the reflection and transmission coefficients be *r*s and *t*s, respectively.
[src:physically-based-rendering/fresnel-equations] Under the sign convention used in this article, a positive reflection or transmission coefficient is one that preserves the direction of the *transverse* field, meaning (in this context) the field normal to the plane of incidence.
[src:physically-based-rendering/fresnel-equations] For the *s* polarization, that means the **E** field.
[src:physically-based-rendering/fresnel-equations] If the incident, reflected, and transmitted **E** fields (in the above equations) are in the *z*-direction ("out of the page"), then the respective **H** fields are in the directions of the red arrows, since **k**, **E**, **H** form a right-handed orthogonal triad.
[src:physically-based-rendering/fresnel-equations] The **H** fields may therefore be described by their components in the directions of those arrows, denoted by *H*i, *H*r, *H*t.
[src:physically-based-rendering/fresnel-equations] For the *p* polarization, the incident, reflected, and transmitted **E** fields are parallel to the red arrows and may therefore be described by their components in the directions of those arrows.
[src:physically-based-rendering/fresnel-equations] Let those components be *E*i, *E*r, *E*t (redefining the symbols for the new context).
[src:physically-based-rendering/fresnel-equations] Let the reflection and transmission coefficients be *r*p and *t*p.
[src:physically-based-rendering/fresnel-equations] If the **E** fields are in the directions of the red arrows, then, in order for **k**, **E**, **H** to form a right-handed orthogonal triad, the respective **H** fields must be in the −*z*-direction ("into the page") and may therefore be described by their components in that direction.
[src:physically-based-rendering/fresnel-equations] This is consistent with the adopted sign convention, namely that a positive reflection or transmission coefficient is one that preserves the direction of the transverse field (the **H** field in the case of the *p* polarization).
[src:physically-based-rendering/fresnel-equations] So, for the incident, reflected, and transmitted **H** fields, let the respective components in the −*z*-direction be *H*i, *H*r, *H*t.
[src:physically-based-rendering/fresnel-equations] At *grazing incidence* (*θ*i → 90°), we again have cos *θ*i → 0, hence *r*p → −1 and *t*p → 0.
[src:physically-based-rendering/fresnel-equations] Comparing (**23**) and (**24**) with (**15**) and (**16**), we see that at *normal* incidence, under the adopted sign convention, the transmission coefficients for the two polarizations are equal, whereas the reflection coefficients have equal magnitudes but opposite signs.
[src:physically-based-rendering/fresnel-equations] While this clash of signs is a disadvantage of the convention, the attendant advantage is that the signs agree at *grazing* incidence.
[src:physically-based-rendering/fresnel-equations] The *Poynting vector* for a wave is a vector whose component in any direction is the *irradiance* (power per unit area) of that wave on a surface perpendicular to that direction.
[src:physically-based-rendering/fresnel-equations] For a plane sinusoidal wave the Poynting vector is ⁠1/2⁠‍Re{**E** × **H**∗}, where **E** and **H** are due *only* to the wave in question, and the asterisk denotes complex conjugation.
[src:physically-based-rendering/fresnel-equations] Note that when comparing the powers of two such waves in the same medium and with the same cos *θ*, the impedance and geometric factors mentioned above are identical and cancel out.
[src:physically-based-rendering/fresnel-equations] But in computing the power *transmission* (below), these factors must be taken into account.
[src:physically-based-rendering/fresnel-equations] The simplest way to obtain the power transmission coefficient (*transmissivity*, the ratio of transmitted power to incident power *in the direction normal to the interface*, i.e. the y direction) is to use *R* + *T* = 1 (conservation of energy).
[src:physically-based-rendering/fresnel-equations] In the case of an interface between two lossless media (for which ϵ and μ are *real* and positive), one can obtain these results directly using the squared magnitudes of the amplitude transmission coefficients that we found earlier in equations (**14**) and (**22**).
[src:physically-based-rendering/fresnel-equations] But, for given amplitude (as noted above), the component of the Poynting vector in the y direction is proportional to the geometric factor cos *θ* and inversely proportional to the wave impedance Z.
[src:physically-based-rendering/fresnel-equations] The last two equations apply only to lossless dielectrics, and only at incidence angles smaller than the critical angle (beyond which, of course, *T* = 0).
[src:physically-based-rendering/fresnel-equations] From equations (**4**) and (**5**), we see that two dissimilar media will have the same refractive index, but different admittances, if the ratio of their permeabilities is the inverse of the ratio of their permittivities.
[src:physically-based-rendering/fresnel-equations] When extended to spherical reflection or scattering, this results in the Kerker effect for Mie scattering.
[src:physically-based-rendering/fresnel-equations] Since the Fresnel equations were developed for optics, they are usually given for non-magnetic materials.
[src:physically-based-rendering/fresnel-equations] The power transmissions can then be found from *T* = 1 − *R*.
[src:physically-based-rendering/fresnel-equations] For equal permeabilities (e.g., non-magnetic media), if *θ*i and *θ*t are *complementary*, we can substitute sin *θ*t for cos *θ*i, and sin *θ*i for cos *θ*t, so that the numerator in equation (**31**) becomes *n*2‍sin *θ*t − *n*1‍sin *θ*i, which is zero (by Snell's law).
[src:physically-based-rendering/fresnel-equations] Hence *r*p = 0 and only the s-polarized component is reflected.
[src:physically-based-rendering/fresnel-equations] This is what happens at the Brewster angle.
[src:physically-based-rendering/fresnel-equations] Although it is not encountered in practice, the equations can also apply to the case of two media with a common permittivity but different refractive indices due to different permeabilities.
[src:physically-based-rendering/fresnel-equations] From equations (**4**) and (**5**), if *ϵ* is fixed instead of *μ*, then Y becomes *inversely* proportional to n, with the result that the subscripts 1 and 2 in equations (**29**) to (**38**) are interchanged (due to the additional step of multiplying the numerator and denominator by *n*1*n*2).
[src:physically-based-rendering/fresnel-equations] Hence, in (**29**) and (**31**), the expressions for *r*s and *r*p in terms of refractive indices will be interchanged, so that Brewster's angle (**39**) will give *r*s = 0 instead of *r*p = 0, and any beam reflected at that angle will be p-polarized instead of s-polarized.
[src:physically-based-rendering/fresnel-equations] Similarly, Fresnel's sine law will apply to the p polarization instead of the s polarization, and his tangent law to the s polarization instead of the p polarization.
[src:physically-based-rendering/fresnel-equations] This switch of polarizations has an analog in the old mechanical theory of light waves (see *§ History*, above).
[src:physically-based-rendering/fresnel-equations] Thus the condition of equal permittivities and unequal permeabilities, although not realistic, is of some historical interest.
[src:physically-based-rendering/microfacet] A **specular highlight** is the bright spot of light that appears on shiny objects when illuminated (for example, see image on right).
[src:physically-based-rendering/microfacet] Specular highlights are important in 3D computer graphics, as they provide a strong visual cue for the shape of an object and its location with respect to light sources in the scene.
[src:physically-based-rendering/microfacet] The term *specular* means that light is perfectly reflected in a mirror-like way from the light source to the viewer.
[src:physically-based-rendering/microfacet] Thus, a specularly reflecting surface would show a specular highlight as the perfectly sharp reflected image of a light source.
[src:physically-based-rendering/microfacet] However, many shiny objects show blurred specular highlights.
[src:physically-based-rendering/microfacet] This can be explained by the existence of **microfacets**.
[src:physically-based-rendering/microfacet] We assume that surfaces that are not perfectly smooth are composed of many very tiny facets, each of which is a perfect specular reflector.
[src:physically-based-rendering/microfacet] These microfacets have normals that are distributed about the normal of the approximating smooth surface.
[src:physically-based-rendering/microfacet] The degree to which microfacet normals differ from the smooth surface normal is determined by the roughness of the surface.
[src:physically-based-rendering/microfacet] At points on the object where the smooth normal is close to the half-angle direction, many of the microfacets point in the half-angle direction and so the specular highlight is bright.
[src:physically-based-rendering/microfacet] As one moves away from the center of the highlight, the smooth normal and the half-angle direction get farther apart; the number of microfacets oriented in the half-angle direction falls, and so the intensity of the highlight falls off to zero.
[src:physically-based-rendering/microfacet] The specular highlight often reflects the color of the light source, not the color of the reflecting object.
[src:physically-based-rendering/microfacet] This is because many materials have a thin layer of clear material above the surface of the pigmented material.
[src:physically-based-rendering/microfacet] For example, plastic is made up of tiny beads of color suspended in a clear polymer and human skin often has a thin layer of oil or sweat above the pigmented cells.
[src:physically-based-rendering/microfacet] Such materials will show specular highlights in which all parts of the color spectrum are reflected equally.
[src:physically-based-rendering/microfacet] On metallic materials such as gold the color of the specular highlight will reflect the color of the material.
[src:physically-based-rendering/microfacet] A number of different models exist to predict the distribution of microfacets.
[src:physically-based-rendering/microfacet] Most assume that the microfacet normals are distributed evenly around the normal; these models are called **isotropic**.
[src:physically-based-rendering/microfacet] If microfacets are distributed with a preference for a certain direction along the surface, the distribution is **anisotropic**.
[src:physically-based-rendering/microfacet] Where *R* is the mirror reflection of the light vector off the surface, and *V* is the viewpoint vector.
[src:physically-based-rendering/microfacet] Where *N* is the smooth surface normal and *H* is the half-angle direction (the direction vector midway between *L*, the vector to the light, and *V*, the viewpoint vector).
[src:physically-based-rendering/microfacet] The number *n* is called the Phong exponent, and is a user-chosen value that controls the apparent smoothness of the surface.
[src:physically-based-rendering/microfacet] These equations imply that the distribution of microfacet normals is an approximately Gaussian distribution (for large n ), or approximately Pearson type II distribution, of the corresponding angle.
[src:physically-based-rendering/microfacet] While this is a useful heuristic and produces believable results, it is not a physically based model.
[src:physically-based-rendering/microfacet] A slightly better model of microfacet distribution can be created using a Gaussian distribution.
[src:physically-based-rendering/microfacet] where *m* is a constant between 0 and 1 that controls the apparent smoothness of the surface.
[src:physically-based-rendering/microfacet] where *$\sigma$* is the rms slope of the surface microfacets (the roughness of the material).
[src:physically-based-rendering/microfacet] Compared to the empirical models above, this function "gives the absolute magnitude of the reflectance without introducing arbitrary constants; the disadvantage is that it requires more computation".
[src:physically-based-rendering/microfacet] Also note that the product of $\cos(\alpha )$ and a surface distribution function is normalized over the half-sphere which is obeyed by this function.
[src:physically-based-rendering/microfacet] The Heidrich–Seidel. distribution is a simple anisotropic distribution, based on the Phong model.
[src:physically-based-rendering/microfacet] It can be used to model surfaces that have small parallel grooves or fibers, such as brushed metal, satin, and hair.
[src:physically-based-rendering/microfacet] First we need to correct original direction of fiber *D* to be perpendicular to real surface normal *N*.
[src:physically-based-rendering/microfacet] It is expected that fiber is cylindrical.
[src:physically-based-rendering/microfacet] Note the fact that normal of fiber depends on light position.
[src:physically-based-rendering/microfacet] Calculation of *R* and *P* are expensive operation.
[src:physically-based-rendering/microfacet] The Ward anisotropic distribution uses two user-controllable parameters *αx* and *αy* to control the anisotropy.
[src:physically-based-rendering/microfacet] If the two parameters are equal, then an isotropic highlight results.
[src:physically-based-rendering/microfacet] The specular term is zero if *N*·*L* < 0 or *N*·*V* < 0.
[src:physically-based-rendering/microfacet] The vector *V* is the viewing direction, *L* is the direction from the surface point to the light, *H* is the half-angle direction between *V* and *L*, *N* is the surface normal, and *X* and *Y* are two orthogonal vectors in the normal plane which specify the anisotropic directions.
[src:physically-based-rendering/microfacet] Here D is the Beckmann distribution factor as above and F is the Fresnel term.
[src:physically-based-rendering/microfacet] For performance reasons, in real-time 3D graphics Schlick's approximation is often used to approximate the Fresnel term.
[src:physically-based-rendering/microfacet] In these formulas V is the vector to the camera or eye, H is the half-angle vector, L is the vector to the light source and N is the normal vector, and α is the angle between H and N.
[src:physically-based-rendering/microfacet] If desired, different distributions (usually, using the same distribution function with different values of *m* or *n*) can be combined using a weighted average.
[src:physically-based-rendering/microfacet] This is useful for modelling, for example, surfaces that have small smooth and rough patches rather than uniform roughness.
[src:physically-based-rendering/physically-based-rendering] Starting in the 1980s, a number of rendering researchers worked on establishing a solid theoretical basis for rendering, including physical correctness.
[src:physically-based-rendering/physically-based-rendering] An early system, Radiance, for lighting design and architecture, was presented in Greg Ward's 1994 SIGGRAPH paper, "The RADIANCE Lighting Simulation and Rendering System," which may have introduced the phrase "physically-based rendering".
[src:physically-based-rendering/physically-based-rendering] Other work was done at the Cornell University Program of Computer Graphics; a 1997 paper from that lab describes the work done at Cornell in this area to that point.
[src:physically-based-rendering/physically-based-rendering] "Physically Based Shading" was introduced by Yoshiharu Gotanda during the course Physically-Based Shading Models in Film and Game Production at the SIGGRAPH 2010.
[src:physically-based-rendering/physically-based-rendering] And followed by the course Physically Based Shading in Theory and Practice organised by Stephen Hill and Stephen McAuley between 2012 and 2020.
[src:physically-based-rendering/physically-based-rendering] The phrase "Physically Based Rendering" was more widely popularized by Matt Pharr, Greg Humphreys, and Pat Hanrahan in their book of the same name from 2004, a seminal work in modern computer graphics that won its authors a Technical Achievement Academy Award for special effects.
[src:physically-based-rendering/physically-based-rendering] The first successful, yet partial implementation of physically-based rendering in a video game can be found in the 2013 title *Remember Me*, that despite being built on a game engine not natively supporting this technology (Unreal Engine 3) was properly modified to accommodate this feature.
[src:physically-based-rendering/physically-based-rendering] Despite being a moderate approach to PBR, its accuracy has been further refined with posterior titles such as *Ryse: Son of Rome* and *Killzone Shadow Fall*, released on the same year, until the current state of PBR advancements in the 2020s.
[src:physically-based-rendering/physically-based-rendering] PBR is, as Joe Wilson puts it, "more of a concept than a strict set of rules" – but the concept contains several distinctive points of note.
[src:physically-based-rendering/physically-based-rendering] One of these is that – unlike many previous models that sought to differentiate surfaces between non-reflective and reflective – PBR recognizes that, in the real world, as John Hable puts it, "everything is shiny".
[src:physically-based-rendering/physically-based-rendering] Even "flat" or "matte" surfaces in the real world such as concrete will reflect a small degree of light, and many metals and liquids will reflect a great deal of it.
[src:physically-based-rendering/physically-based-rendering] Another thing that PBR models attempt to do is to integrate photogrammetry - measurements from photographs of real-world materials - to study and replicate real physical ranges of values to accurately simulate albedo, gloss, reflectivity, and other physical properties.
[src:physically-based-rendering/physically-based-rendering] Finally, PBR puts a great deal of emphasis on microfacets, and will often contain additional textures and mathematical models intended to model small-scale specular highlights and cavities resulting from smoothness or roughness in addition to traditional specular or reflectivity maps.
[src:physically-based-rendering/physically-based-rendering] PBR often utilize Bidirectional scattering distribution functions to calculate the visible light reflected at a given point on surfaces.
[src:physically-based-rendering/physically-based-rendering] Common techniques use approximations and simplified models that try to fit approximate models to more accurate data from other more time consuming methods or laboratory measurements (such as those of a gonioreflectometer).
[src:physically-based-rendering/physically-based-rendering] Thanks to high performance and low costs of modern hardware it has become feasible to use PBR not only for industrial but also entertainment purposes wherever photorealistic images are desired, such as video games or movie making.
[src:physically-based-rendering/physically-based-rendering] A typical application provides an intuitive graphical user interface that allows artists to define and layer materials with arbitrary properties and to assign them to a given 2D or 3D object to recreate the appearance of any synthetic or organic material.
[src:physically-based-rendering/physically-based-rendering] Environments can be defined with procedural shaders or textures as well as procedural geometry or meshes or point clouds.
[src:physically-based-rendering/physically-based-rendering] If possible all changes are made visible in real-time and therefore allow for quick iterations.
